Below is a **single, self‑contained unit** that shows how you can expose a C++ iterator (from *libpcapng*) to OCaml and let OCaml code run a user supplied function on every frame.  

The unit consists of  

* `pcapng.mli` – the public OCaml interface (what the user sees)  
* `pcapng_stubs.cpp` – the C‑C++ glue code that implements the interface.  

The design uses **abstract types** (`capture` and `frame`) that are backed by C++ objects and a **single “iterator‑callback” primitive** `iter_frames`.  The user supplies an OCaml closure of type `frame -> unit`; the stub walks the C++ iterator and calls the closure for each frame.

---

## 1. `pcapng.mli` – public OCaml interface

```ocaml
(*--------------------------------------------------------------------
   libpcapng OCaml bindings
   --------------------------------------------------------------------*)

(** A handle for an opened pcapng file.  The value is opaque – it is
    managed by the C++ library and freed automatically when the
    OCaml value is garbage collected (or when [close] is called). *)
type capture

(** A handle for a single frame (packet) returned by the iterator.
    The value is also opaque; it is a thin wrapper around a C++ object
    that lives as long as the corresponding [capture] is alive. *)
type frame

(** Open a pcapng file for reading.  Raises [Invalid_argument] if the
    file cannot be opened or parsed. *)
val open_file : string -> capture

(** Close a capture and free the underlying C++ object.  It is safe
    (but a no‑op) to call this on a value that has already been GC‑ed. *)
val close : capture -> unit

(** Iterate over all frames in the capture, invoking the supplied OCaml
    function on each frame.  The iteration stops as soon as the OCaml
    function raises an exception – the exception is propagated to the
    caller of [iter_frames]. *)
val iter_frames : capture -> (frame -> unit) -> unit

(** -----------------------------------------------------------------
    Accessors for a single frame.  All functions raise [Invalid_argument]
    if the underlying C++ object is no longer valid (e.g. after the
    parent capture has been closed).
    ----------------------------------------------------------------- *)

(** Timestamp of the frame (seconds since the Unix epoch). *)
val timestamp : frame -> float

(** Length of the captured packet (including the Ethernet header). *)
val captured_len : frame -> int

(** Original length of the packet on the wire. *)
val original_len : frame -> int

(** Raw packet bytes.  The returned string is a fresh copy; it can be
    safely mutated by OCaml code. *)
val data : frame -> string

(** Example helper: return the Ethernet source MAC address as a string
    of six bytes (binary).  Returns [None] if the frame is not an
    Ethernet frame. *)
val eth_src : frame -> string option

(** Example helper: return the Ethernet destination MAC address. *)
val eth_dst : frame -> string option
```

### How a user would normally use the library

```ocaml
open Pcapng

let () =
  let cap = open_file "sample.pcapng" in
  (* Print a short summary of each frame *)
  iter_frames cap (fun fr ->
    Printf.printf "ts=%f len=%d\n%!"
      (timestamp fr) (captured_len fr));
  close cap
```

